{"id":"bio-flow-1","goldState":"flowing","turns":[{"role":"tutor","content":"Why does a leaf look green?"},{"role":"pupil","content":"Chlorophyll absorbs red and blue light and reflects green, so the green is what bounces back to us. It's also why plants kept in dim light grow leggy — they stretch toward the wavelengths they can actually use."}],"signals":{"windowSec":50,"scaffoldUseCount":0,"avgMessageLength":215,"questionRatio":0},"lessonTitle":"Photosynthesis","lessonSubject":"Biology","criticalConcepts":["chlorophyll","light absorption"]}
{"id":"bio-flow-2","goldState":"flowing","turns":[{"role":"tutor","content":"What happens to the glucose a plant makes?"},{"role":"pupil","content":"Some is used straight away in respiration for energy, some is stored as starch in the leaves and roots, and some becomes cellulose for the cell walls. So it's not just food, it's building material too."}],"signals":{"windowSec":48,"scaffoldUseCount":0,"avgMessageLength":205,"questionRatio":0},"lessonTitle":"Photosynthesis","lessonSubject":"Biology","criticalConcepts":["glucose","starch"]}
{"id":"math-flow-1","goldState":"flowing","turns":[{"role":"tutor","content":"How would you find 15% of 240?"},{"role":"pupil","content":"I'd do 10% which is 24, then 5% is half of that so 12, add them to get 36. You can always break a percentage into 10s and 5s and add the chunks."}],"signals":{"windowSec":40,"scaffoldUseCount":0,"avgMessageLength":175,"questionRatio":0},"lessonTitle":"Percentages","lessonSubject":"Maths","criticalConcepts":["percentage of an amount"]}
{"id":"eng-flow-1","goldState":"flowing","turns":[{"role":"tutor","content":"Why might the poet repeat the word 'alone' at the end of each verse?"},{"role":"pupil","content":"It builds the isolation up — each time it lands harder because we expect it now, and the repetition makes the loneliness feel inescapable, like it's closing in on the speaker rather than fading."}],"signals":{"windowSec":55,"scaffoldUseCount":0,"avgMessageLength":230,"questionRatio":0},"lessonTitle":"Poetry: imagery","lessonSubject":"English","criticalConcepts":["repetition","tone"]}
{"id":"hist-flow-1","goldState":"flowing","turns":[{"role":"tutor","content":"Why did trench warfare lead to stalemate?"},{"role":"pupil","content":"Defence was far stronger than attack — machine guns and barbed wire cut down anyone going over the top, so neither side could break through, and gaining a few hundred metres cost thousands of lives. That's why it barely moved for years."}],"signals":{"windowSec":52,"scaffoldUseCount":0,"avgMessageLength":250,"questionRatio":0},"lessonTitle":"WW1: the Western Front","lessonSubject":"History","criticalConcepts":["stalemate","defensive technology"]}
{"id":"bio-flow-3","goldState":"flowing","turns":[{"role":"tutor","content":"How does the structure of the alveoli help gas exchange?"},{"role":"pupil","content":"They're tiny and there are millions of them, so the surface area is huge. The walls are one cell thick so the diffusion distance is short, and they're surrounded by capillaries to keep the concentration gradient steep. All three speed up diffusion."}],"signals":{"windowSec":58,"scaffoldUseCount":0,"avgMessageLength":265,"questionRatio":0},"lessonTitle":"The lungs","lessonSubject":"Biology","criticalConcepts":["surface area","diffusion"]}
